          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">
         Bulgaria green lit for Euro</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
          Summary: Bulgaria is set to adopt the Euro at the beginning of 2026.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Bulgaria will <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-jun-25-spotlights-h2-3-adopt-the-euro" target="_blank">adopt the euro</a> on January 1st, 2026, following approval from the European Commission and the European Central Bank (ECB). It delayed its original 2024 target due to high inflation of 9.5%. However, they expect inflation to ease to 3.6% this year and drop to 1.8% by 2026.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       Adopting the euro brings benefits, including easier trade, increased investor confidence, and a gateway to ECB support. Bulgarian leaders believe euro adoption is a big step toward deeper integration with Europe. However, it has caused domestic backlash. Protests <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-jun-25-spotlights-h2-4-led-by-nationalist" target="_blank">led by nationalist</a> and pro-Russian groups fear a loss of economic control and cultural identity. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        If all approvals are granted, Bulgaria will become the Eurozoneâ€™s 21st member and the poorest country in the bloc. Bulgaria's current currency, the lev, has been pegged to the euro since 1999 to facilitate an easier transition. Bulgaria has been a part of the European Union since 2007. </p>
        
        </mj-text>
