          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
       Unorganized scramble for Central Asia
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
         Summary: The EU and the US need to have a plan to obtain Central Asian resources.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
            Italian PM Giorgia Meloniâ€™s recent trip to Central Asia highlights the Westâ€™s <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-jun-25-analysis-h1-5-struggle-to-match-words" target="_blank">struggle to match words</a> with measures. By mentioning figures like Marco Polo and Halford Mackinder, Meloni sought to link Italyâ€™s goals to a broader narrative of trade and geopolitics. However, her reference to Mackinderâ€™s old heartland theory highlights a bigger concern. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Meloni, being out of touch, lacks strategies to address the challenges of global supply chains, green energy, and water scarcity. Even with the announcement of $7.7 B in agreements with Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan, Meloniâ€™s visit, similar to other EU and US efforts, was heavy on symbolism but lacking specific details. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Central Asian leaders are clear about their needs. They want industrial localization, technology transfers, and education exchanges, not just raw resource extraction. They want genuine long-term cooperation. 
          </p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        If Western powers want to compete with China and Russia in the region, they must go beyond vague statements. They need to listen more to Central Asians and invest in infrastructure, as well as support sustainable development. 
          </p>
         
        </mj-text>
