   How did Indonesia become the largest Muslim country in the world?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/indonesian-islam-cultural-diversity-history.jpg" alt="Indonesian Islam is characterized by diversity, as each region has experienced its unique history, shaped by distinct and separate influences" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>Indonesian Islam is characterized by diversity, as each region has experienced its unique history, shaped by distinct and separate influences. Credits: Brookings</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        Indonesia has 207Mn Muslims, the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-jun-25-foundations-h1-12-largest-muslim-population" target="_blank">largest Muslim population</a> in the world. This growth came not through conquest, but through centuries of peaceful influence, mainly from trade. Starting in the 13th century, Muslim traders from the Middle East, India, and China utilized key trade routes, such as the Strait of Malacca, to reach ports in Indonesia. 
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Local rulers began converting to Islam to strengthen ties with Muslim merchants and gain regional power. This spread the faith through coastal Sumatra, Java, and beyond. Islamic sultanates emerged, constructing mosques, fostering education, and supporting scholars. Traditional customs blended with Islamic teachings. Over time, Islam has become a part of the Indonesian identity.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        While present-day Indonesia is a secular state, Islamic culture still shapes its society. Conservative Islamic extremism in politics has grown, especially after the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-jun-25-foundations-h1-13-2017-jakarta-election" target="_blank">2017 Jakarta election</a> and <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-jun-25-foundations-h1-14-ahok-s-blasphemy-trial" target="_blank">Ahokâ€™s blasphemy hearing</a>. However, most Indonesian Muslims support tolerance and pluralism. Radical groups remain a small minority, except in the province of Aceh, which is semi-autonomous. 
        </p>
        </mj-text>
